            <p>
                <title>Recall Information from Previous Courses</title> \subsection{Function Vocabulary}
            </p>

            <definition>
                <title>domain</title>

                <p>
                    The domain of a function <m>f</m> is the <em>largest</em> set of <em>real numbers</em> for which the value <em>$f(x)$</em> is a <em>real number</em>.\\ \\ Things to look out for
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ul>
                        \item Division by <em>zero</em>\item <em>Even</em> roots of <em>negative</em> numbers
                    </ul>
                </p>

                <note>
                    <p>
                        For word problems/verbal descriptions, the domain depends on the real-world <em>context</em> of the model.\\ \\
                    </p>
                </note>
            </definition>

            <example>
                <p>
                    \textit{Finding the domain of a function from an equation}\\ undefinedpace*{12 pt} <m>f(x)=3x+2</m> \hspace{\hfill} <m>g(x)=\dfrac{3x+2}{x+1}</m> \hspace{\hfill} <m>h(x)=\sqrt{x-3}</m>
                </p>
            </example>

            <p>
                undefinedpace{\stretch{1}}
            </p>

            <definition>
                <title>zero</title>

                <p>
                    If <m>f</m> is a function and <m>r</m> is a real number for which <em>$f(r)=0$</em>, then <m>r</m> is a zero of <m>f</m>.
                    In other words, <m>r</m> is an <em>x-intercept</em> of the <em>graph</em> of <m>f</m>.
                </p>
            </definition>

            <definition>
                <title>maximum</title>

                <p>
                    The <em>maximum</em> of a function <m>f</m> is the <em>largest</em> value in the <em>range</em> of <m>f</m>.
                    On the graph of <m>f</m>, the maximum is the <em>y-coordinate</em> of a point at the <em>top</em> of a <em>peak</em>.
                </p>
            </definition>

            <definition>
                <title>minimum</title>

                <p>
                    The <em>minimum</em> of a function <m>f</m> is the <em>smallest</em> value in the <em>range</em> of <m>f</m>.
                    On the graph of <m>f</m>, the minimum is the <em>y-coordinate</em> of a point at the <em>bottom</em> of a <em>valley</em>.
                </p>
            </definition>

            <p>
                \newpage
            </p>

            <definition>
                <title>even</title>

                <p>
                    A function <m>f</m> is <em>even</em> if and only if it is symmetric with respect to the <em>$y$-axis</em>.\\ <em>$f(x)=f(-x)$</em> for every <m>x</m>-value in the domain of <m>f</m>
                </p>
            </definition>

            <definition>
                <title>odd</title>

                <p>
                    A function <m>f</m> is <em>odd</em> if and only if it is symmetric with respect to the <em>origin</em>.\\ <em>$f(-x)=-f(x)$</em> for every <m>x</m>-value in the domain of <m>f</m>
                </p>
            </definition>

            <p>
                %\newpage
            </p>

            <example>
                <p>
                    \textit{(Determining Symmetry from an Equation)}\\ \\ <m>f(x)=x^4+3x^2-x</m>
                </p>
            </example>

