            <p>
                \subsection{Transformations of Functions}
            </p>

            <definition>
                <title>transformation</title>

                <p>
                    <em>Transformations</em> are rule-based <em>changes</em> to the graph of a function.
                    Each transformation can occur in one of two directions: <em>vertical</em> or <em>horizontal</em>.
                    There are three types of transformations:
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ul>
                        \item <em>Translation</em>- This represents a change in <em>location</em>.\item <em>Dilation</em>- This represents a change in <em>size</em>.\item <em>Reflection</em>- This represents a change in <em>orientation</em>.
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </definition>

            <p>
                Given a function <m>f(x)</m>, a transformation of <m>f(x)</m> is a function of the form
            </p>

            <p>
                undefinedpace{-.25in} \begin{center} undefinedge{
                <men>
                    g(x)=\mathbf{a}\cdot f\left(\mathbf{b}\left(x-\mathbf{c}\right)\right)+\mathbf{d}
                </men>
            </p>

            <p>
                } \end{center}
            </p>

            <p>
                undefinedpace{.5in}
            </p>

            <p>
                \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{2}
            </p>

            <tabular>
                {l l}\hline <em>$\mathbf{a</em>$: vertical dilation and/or reflection} & negative: reflect over $x$-axis\\ & $\mathbf{|a|}>1$ taller \qquad $\mathbf{|a|}<1$ shorter\\ \hline <em>$\mathbf{b</em>$: horizontal dilation and/or reflection} & negative: reflect over $y$-axis\\ & $\mathbf{|b|}>1$ narrower \qquad $\mathbf{|b|}<1$ wider\\ \hline <em>$\mathbf{c</em>$: horizontal translation} & $\mathbf{c}$ positive (subtraction from $x$): right\\ & $\mathbf{c}$ negative (addition to x): left\\ \hline <em>$\mathbf{d</em>$: vertical translation} & $\mathbf{d}$ positive: up\\ & $\mathbf{d}$ negative: down\\ \hline
            </tabular>

            <p>
                undefinedpace*{.25in}
            </p>

            <p>
                \noindent{Note: Follow the order of operations to perform multiple transformations in sequence: <m>\mathbf{c}</m>, then <m>\mathbf{b}</m>, then <m>\mathbf{a}</m>, then <m>\mathbf{d}</m>.}
            </p>

            <p>
                \newpage
            </p>

            <example>
                <p>
                    \textit{(Transforming Points)}\\Describe the sequence of transformations of the graph of <m>f(x)=x^2</m> to obtain the graph of <m>g(x)=-3(x+2)^2 -1</m>, then sketch <m>g(x)</m>.
                </p>
            </example>

